On the other hand, traditional or conservative families are rare to be found in the Republic of Cyprus. In this case, divorce is common and women play an equal role in decision-making. Moreover, according to law, it does not matter if the marriage was solemnized on the secular or religious side.

Marital Property in the North

Just like in the Republic of Cyprus, in both 1958 and 1960 Northern Cyprus legislation, both civil and religious marriages were unified. Before 1960, all marriages were governed by the british law.

In the North, all inherited property is unified to be shared equally among the children following the passing of the parents. It is to be noted that before this law, inherited property was divided equally among the sons. In case of several other spouses in respect of all joint property.

When a divorce occurs in Northern Cyprus, it is, however, possible for a couple to come to a mutual agreement regarding how they would want to divide their property.

When a divorce occurs, the marital property will be divided according to what was earned throughout the marriage.
